segments.text: I guess a couple of the people that had as much influence on my life would have been probably Bill Amings, who ended up dying at a very early age, but an outstanding patrol missionary.
What was outstanding about him?
He cared about people.
And even though he was tough and everything, you know, being there with them,
chop in one hand and butcher in the other.
And it sometimes didn't be there way before we get there and have a whole board just cut.
And at that point in time, in petroleum engineering, they really didn't have that many good textbooks.
And that resolved most of what they gave George through handouts and so forth and what they put on the blackboard.
And the other one was, of course, Bob White.
And he's still there.
Describe him.
He was a completely different type of person.
And I think he probably got a lot of ideas maybe from Harold Vance who was head of the department before Fred Stevens and then Bob White.
It just kind of hit the flame.
I was kind of like an old miner.
I was just thinking, oh, I'll just drill another foot and hit the mother load down there.
That miner's going to chip another six inches and he's going to rip the mother load.
I think guiding, guiding.
I was into direction, which we might take.
At one time, I thought probably I was going to retire, major oil company, engineer, vice president, or something.
But after having been around him enough, I finally realized that the only way you really want to do it is to get out and do it on your own.
All right, let's go to some other, what about any important people that
In chemistry, physics?
Well, I had a real interest in them.
There were several interesting professors.
I think it's always fun to talk about them.
Like Muggles Harder.
No, no, no, no.
It's Texas A&M.
Texas A&M.
Snuggs.
Oh yes, please share it with us.
Every time you come in with a grin, you hear, hello, thank you, thank you, you know, this, that, that.
You're just all so enthusiastic.
And then I guess you're physically, that one's a quantity, but I believe in physical chemistry, I think it's a little bit harder.
Oh gosh, you just never understand what's going on.
Maybe in a dirty shirt and else.
probably hurt again.

I had no idea, but he just had that nickname.
It wasn't that dirty.
He did it for some reason.
Did you ever have chemistry with John Beckham?
No.
Because I think his nickname was Foghorn.
He had a very strong voice.
Let's see, math?
I didn't have the same type of feelings towards English as I did the other day.
Although I did find that it just looked up.
In other faculty, other disciplines that you can talk about?
I can't remember the guy that taught us.
I think it was a book on the story of mankind, I believe.
And you didn't take any history, probably.
State law would be changed right after you graduated, requiring six.
I took one for history and government.
And that was the only one I couldn't work in, so I had to do it by correspondence with the dressing room.
Let's see, were there any, did you ever have any interaction with John Calhoun?
Was he?
I got there after.
I read the 55.
So he was there.
Oh, I'd love to.
I'd love to.
Still as bright as can be.
Still on the campus every day.
His book is one of the best reservoir books in the world.
He's just got the worst table of contents and index.
Were there any counselor, advisors that perhaps in the core, MSC?
Student life, housing?
Well, the reason I guess I'm here is because I'm a law student, and I've always been involved in politics, even though I did not run for an office or anything like that.
Since out of here, as a freshman, I was a class president with President Clayton, and was a student senator as a result of that.
I had to be around a lot of people the freshman year that I probably wouldn't have if I hadn't been elected to it.
So I was around Wally Moon.
Wally Moon was the coach of the freshman baseball team.
I grew up in a baseball field, and on my way down there, I thought that I could probably just walk up, you know, and see the best player going.
One of the last couple of guys that was cut, but after about six or seven or eight games, I ended up being cut off the team.
And I attribute that to my classmate, Joe Hargrove.
He didn't lose a game in his senior year.
He was like 16 or 17-0.
He had a curve like he couldn't win.
pitching from the left hand side.
I haven't seen a curve like that.
But anyway, I enjoyed the baseball experience, the student senate, and all of those types of things.
As a junior, I learned a handful.
on students any time, when elected again, and ended up getting on the welcome committee.
Bonkers Lane didn't recognize the need for students to go out and welcome other universities to Texas A&M campus.
particularly when I took him away from his classes.
I really enjoyed all that, but barely got through third grade.
I think all students had to go through something like that.
What was the nickname y'all gave to Professor Samay?
Oh, man, I don't know.
Later it would be Mom.
I don't know whether y'all called him Mom, but later they would call him Mom Samay.
I'm sure he's one of the finest guys in the world.
I said, where is he?
He was one of the hardest professors I have ever seen anywhere.
Did you ever have time?
I outlined that whole book before the final just to pass the course.
But the one thing he could have asked, I couldn't.
But I could derive anything to get the final.

Thompson?
Yeah.

great teacher in the 60's.

from the Petroleum Engineering Club to the Engineering Council.

I'll never forget going back

The first patrol meeting here, just ahead, monthly, at night.

I'll call you anyway next time.
It was a junior representative.
The president conducts the club.
I asked the junior representative if he wants to say anything.
You know, they were saying that the props are holding people too long.
So if any of you guys have trouble, just let me know.
Who is that guy?
The senior year I was elected as the president of the Petroleum Industry Club, vice president of the client, student senator, and a few other things.
Probably if you looked through the annuals, you'd see all this type of stuff.
MSC.
Tell me what role it played in the life of the student in your days.
All of the meetings that we had, the students hadn't met over there all the time.
I assume the problem still does.
The ballroom was there.
I know we had some of the smaller dances there.
I was looking back there and I saw, it's interesting, my wife, she's a fish baller, she's a sophomore, she's a military baller, she's a junior here and a senior there.
So... Did you have any interaction with Wayne Stark?
Very, very little.
I was chairman of the Muster Committee my senior year.
And as a result, I had quite a bit to do with the executive director of the college students.
Herbie?
Yeah.
Still going strong.
Yeah.
Describe that muster.
Where was it held and what did you do?
It was held on the steps of the MSC.
My first year it was held in that system construction, which is the Jack Williams building, if I can write your name.
It was held there.
Late afternoon, night, when?
Probably about, it was late afternoon, about probably 5, probably 5, maybe 5.15, 5.30. Who came?
Let's see, yeah, I had to get it.
Four Star Channel, Air Force.
I saw something in the Aggie just the other day.
Something's happened, I think, too.
But who attended in the audience?
Almost all seniors were there, particularly in the fourth.
Did it make any kind of emotional impression on you, muster, at that point?
Certainly not as an impression.
But on and on, it got more important.
I had not only a roommate, but I also had another gentleman who was killed in another outfit.
In fact, I ended up switching over to the artillery my junior year.
and I didn't want to let four years and then decided two, so I ended up getting into Coastal Artillery.
Ended up going into the artillery for two years and serving all of El Paso.
Oh, Fort Bliss.
Taught electronics and radar circumstances.
I know of no city that has a more positive relationship
with a military installation in El Paso's fields by Fort Bliss.
I don't believe that.
What about silver caps?
Where was it held and what was done?
Of course, I made two of those as being in the unit where the person had died and belonged to.
And it was in front of the academic building.
Is it still healthy?
I would think so.
Where were the bugles?
Up there.
And what did you and your classmates do after
did y'all did y'all react seriously
What role did silver caps and luster and things like that, what role did those events have in creating your feelings about the institution?
I think it all goes together.
I think it all goes together.
You can't really say which one is the most important.
Certainly, certainly luster right now.
It was very, very big.
I don't know how I would have felt if I had gone there and not been involved.
Probably not nearly as strong as I've been.
Let's see.
Football weekend, home football game weekend.
Describe a typical routine for you as a freshman.
It was just like almost any other thing.
You're right there with a sophomore in your face saying, you get all freshman, you know.
I can't hear you.
Then later on, a few times, my future wife was going to
one year to Kilgore Junior College and then the rest of the time was at North Texas so it was quite a ways off.
She didn't have a car either so it was a little difficult for her to get down there but occasionally she'd come down which she did and we absolutely had a great time.
Now where would she stay?
She stayed one time at the AEMM and one time at the MSC.
Well, more than once in Tennessee.
Several times.
Who paid her rent?
Who paid for the rent?
I'm sure I did.
So it was the young man's responsibility?
Oh, yeah.
And she would come down on the train?
No, usually with another girl.
The freshman ball, her father brought her.
She would normally get there, win on the front, or center, if it was football.
I don't remember it being over one night.
I think it was, you know.
So she got there on Saturday.
Yeah.
You do know that we had classes.
Oh, sure, sure.
Saturday mornings.
That's hard for today's students to accept.
And, you know, they still have those.
Yeah, they can't believe that.
On the football weekend.
Sure, sure.

One thing that was interesting, before the ring dance, she did get down the night before and I was really awaiting her arrival because I needed her to type my evaluation report, term report to Mr. Whiting, which was quite lengthy.
I can remember that
We stayed up the whole night before the ring dance.
So we were not quite at our best the next night.
Describe that ring dance.
Where was it?
Out in the grove.
Do you remember what group played?
No, yeah, because I had a partner responsible, but we just didn't have a real good pick.
Fucked me all these years.
Johnny Long.
Horsetown or something.
I think it'd be the only thing anyone's ever heard.

Oh, boy.
Yeah.
And his bookends.
Those good-looking girls.
Oh, wow.
Wow.

Just the seniors.
They, uh, any seniors.
You know, unfortunately we got no pictures.
which we, in our bedroom, you'll see the rain over here, the two of us, a little younger.
And what if it had rained?
Was there a fallback?
I'm sure it would have been the those days portion of the MSC, but that is so small.
Oh yeah.
For some of the smaller classes, that would have probably worked out, but I don't know.
I heard it started out with over 2,000 in the freshman class, which at that time was rather large.
I think we ended up graduating with about 7,000.
At the ring dance, describe what people wore.
And what kind of conduct was normal?
How did people behave?
Really pretty sane.
I don't remember anything out loud at all.

Well, that just depends.
There's all kinds of...
I can remember a big group of us ended up at the Clay Pits.
Have you heard of the Clay Pits?
Sure.
And what would y'all be doing at the Clay Pits?
Well, what did young people do at the Clay Pits at that time when there was a group?
I'm sure they were going to beer or something.
Just extend the party.
And where did y'all get the beer?
I don't know if it was in the Texan Drive-In or the Triangle or over on Whiskey Bridge, whatever that is.
Describe what Whiskey Bridge was.
It was on the way to Austin, I think.
Farm Road 60 going south.
Yeah, going south, yeah.
And a place to go where you get alcohol and beer.
Did they have any student ID requirement?
Did anybody have to prove their age?
Usually we had somebody in there that we served or something.
So we started in 51 and we had quite a few beds.
If that wasn't the problem.
If somebody wanted to go somewhere and drink a beer,
buy a beer and drink it, where do they go?
You know, I really didn't drink that much.
That's what I can call it.
But usually I'm trying to order a little Pepsi.
It was almost all of it.
Was hard liquors going around?
I don't know.

Uncle Ed?
That's it.
Uncle Ed.
Uncle Ed.

I don't know.

And there's different places.
It was just out of the University that goes by the hill.
Yes, I want to say probably was located not too far from the hill.
My wife said that was one of the first things the guys did when the girls left.
No.

No, it didn't happen on the 31st or some of the 4th.
Oh, OK.

A couple of years when I was there on the weekend, I built there two, three, four times a week.
I had a student wife.

Yeah, they were local.

It leads you in the right direction.
Now, were there some counselor types that students could go to throughout the year to just get advice?
No, I'm not sure.

No.

David Martin as president, living in the president's home.
Oh, that old frame house.
Yeah.

One of the

Not even like the things I've heard some other people do.
I've not heard of them.
No, I have not heard of them.
See, I was there.
